column10:
Has potential but it's not yet good. Hopefully they fix the following:
- the only notable thing about classes is the weapons they get access to. No other unique mechanics, all the stat bonuses they start out with can be overcome with one level-up reward;
- overclock unlocking is clearly meant only to pad out content by forcing you to do runs again and again before you can actually make use of overclocks;
- only some of the overclock options are game changers but most are simple stat bonuses that can be overshadowed by one level-up reward;
- weapons need balancing, there are some mandatory picks and some that are never worth bringing;
- there are game-changing artefacts but the loot table is crowded out by boring stat-boosters;
- enemy variety is low: mostly melees, some spitters, one exploder
- the permanent upgrades are all boring yet mandatory stat-bonuses, there's no choice to be had here, you are expected to grab all of them, which is made super-slow to pad out the lack of content.
- the end-boss has one trick: it jumps on top of you. So all runs oblige you to stack speed and to always clear a path along which you can do laps, no matter what you class/weapons are. There's no other strategy to this fight.
- in general, there's only one meta-strategy and that's to clump up the enemies and trigger a chain explosion. While fun, there are exploders at every wave of every level on every map so even that gets boring.

The consequence of all the above is that, for now, the runs are identical. The only reason to do them is to unlock the few interesting overclocks.

The good news is that all of this [b]can be fixed if the devs try.[/b]

